{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17568890","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17568890"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:23:41+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:23:41+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"21508"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"21508","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/21508"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.35,0.08,0.1,0.1,0.37]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"14377"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116350"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"14377","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/14377"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"21508"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98347"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"37"},{"type":"tags","id":"43"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1315"},{"type":"tags","id":"1571"},{"type":"tags","id":"4980"},{"type":"tags","id":"4983"},{"type":"tags","id":"4985"},{"type":"tags","id":"11110"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"11643"},{"type":"tags","id":"12801"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"35951"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35952"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35953"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35954"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43751"},{"type":"contributions","id":"49711"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116350","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/116350"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 36-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic requesting oral contraception. She has a medical history of migraine without aura and takes sumatriptan as needed. She does not take any other regular medications. She smokes 10 cigarettes per day and has a body mass index of 24 kg/m2. She is adamant that she does not want any injections, implants or intrauterine devices, but wants something highly efficacious. She works as an interstate truck driver and often changes between day and night shifts.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate oral contraceptive option?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Progestogen-only pill containing levonorgestrel (Mini Pill)","Combined pill containing ethinylestradiol and drospirenone (COCP)","Combined pill containing ethinylestradiol and norethisterone (COCP)","Strict use of condoms","Progestogen-only pill containing drospirenone (Slinda)"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has several factors that influence contraceptive choice. While she has migraine without aura (rather than with aura), combined hormonal contraception is still relatively contraindicated (WHO Medical Eligibility Criteria category 3) in women over 35 with migraine. She is a smoker, which at her age is a relative contraindication to oestrogen-containing pills regardless of the number of cigarettes smoked (WHO Medical Eligibility Criteria category 3). Additionally, has a strong preference against any long-acting reversible contraceptive options and her irregular work schedule as a truck driver makes strict timing of medication challenging.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProgestogen-only pill containing drospirenone (Slinda)\u003C/strong\u003E provides effective contraception with a 24-hour missed pill window, making it more forgiving than traditional progestogen-only pills. This is particularly important given her variable work schedule. It inhibits ovulation in 97% of cycles and has a similar effectiveness profile to combined oral contraceptives.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProgestogen-only pill containing levonorgestrel\u003C/strong\u003E (Mini pill, microlut or noriday) requires strict timing within a 3-hour window each day, which would be impractical for this patient given her rotating shift work. While it would be safe given her medical history, the strict timing requirement makes it less suitable.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECombined pill containing ethinylestradiol and drospirenone\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Ecombined pill containing ethinylestradiol and norethisterone\u003C/strong\u003E both contain oestrogen and are relatively contraindicated in women over 35 with migraine (even without aura) due to increased stroke risk. This risk is further increased by her smoking status.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStrict use of condoms\u003C/strong\u003E alone would not be appropriate given the patient\u0027s request for highly efficacious contraception. With typical use, condoms have a failure rate of around 13% per year, compared to less than 1% for hormonal methods when used correctly. While condoms provide protection against sexually transmitted infections, they are not the most reliable form of contraception when used alone.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe presence of migraine in women over 35, particularly when combined with smoking, significantly increases the risk of ischaemic stroke. When combined with oestrogen-containing contraceptives, this risk increases further. Progestogen-only methods do not increase stroke risk and are therefore safe options, with drospirenone-containing preparations offering additional advantages in terms of timing flexibility.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Traditional progestogen-only pills must be taken within a strict 3-hour window each day for optimal effectiveness.","Drospirenone-containing progestogen-only pills (Slinda) have a 24-hour missed pill window, offering a dosing-regimen and efficacy similar to that of combined oral contraceptives."],"references":["Archer DF, Ahrendt HJ, Drouin D. Drospirenone-only oral contraceptive: results from a multicenter noncomparative trial of efficacy, safety and tolerability. Contraception. 2015 Nov;92(5):439-44. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/26232513/","UK MEDICAL ELIGIBILITY CRITERIA [Internet]. Available at: https://www.fsrh.org/Common/Uploaded%20files/Standards-and-Guidance/fsrh-ukmec-full-book-2019.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98347"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"21508"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98347","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/98347"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-28T16:49:46+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-28T16:52:09+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"14377"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116350"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf53","name":"Gynaecology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"37","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/37"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c